BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:GameOn: Life Skills Through Soccer
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260422T170000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260422T180000
UID:69b5a549b48451fc3c08e82c@tpl.bibliocommons.com
DESCRIPTION:Stay confident under pressure\, and connect better with others
 . It's all about building skills\, making friends\, and growing as a playe
 r and a leader through soccer.\nPepy Malonga is the founder of FOOT-IQ\, a
 n educational initiative that uses sport as a platform to help young peopl
 e develop leadership and life skills. Through interactive workshops and yo
 uth programs\, he helps participants explore themes such as communication\
 , teamwork\, decision-making\, and emotional intelligence using engaging s
 port-based scenarios and discussions.\nPepy has led programs with schools\
 , libraries\, and community organizations across Toronto\, creating enviro
 nments where youth build confidence\, reflect on their choices\, and stren
 gthen their leadership potential.\nHis work focuses on helping young peopl
 e understand that leadership is not about performance\, but about mindset\
 , responsibility\, and how they interact with others.\nRegistration requir
 ed. Drop-ins welcome\, but space is limited\n.
LOCATION:Beaches\, Program Room or outdoors (weather permitting)
URL:https://tpl.bibliocommons.com/v2/events/69b5a549b48451fc3c08e82c
X-SOURCE:Toronto Public Library
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Sensory Storytime Social for Neurodivergent Children
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260516T150000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260516T160000
UID:69b41636b48451fc3c08a071@tpl.bibliocommons.com
DESCRIPTION:Join us for a series of adapted Sensory Storytimes for childre
 n aged 4-12 and their families to enjoy stories\, songs\, and rhymes in a 
 sensory-aware environment with sensory tools\, toys and accessories. After
 wards\, join us for a 30-minute Stay and Play activity session where child
 ren can explore sensory bins\, and adults can connect with other parents a
 nd caregivers\, and discover helpful resources.\nThese programs are specif
 ically designed to be welcoming to neurodivergent children\, including aut
 istic children and those with sensory processing differences. The programs
  will take place inside S. Walter Stewart Auditorium\, with access to the 
 Sensory Room. This program is a neurodivergent positive space.\nRegistrant
 s will receive a Venue Guide describing accessibility features\, sensory a
 ccommodations\, and further details a few weeks before the program.\nFor m
 ore information\, please call 416-396-3975 to speak with the Children’s 
 Librarian.\nInformation Collection Notice:\nThe personal information on th
 is form is collected by the Toronto Public Library under the Public Librar
 ies Act\, sections 20(a)\, 20(c)\, and 20(d). The information will only be
  used for event and program registration\, delivery and evaluation. Questi
 ons about how the library handles your information can be directed to Answ
 erline staff at\nanswerline@tpl.ca\n\, 416-397-5981\, 789 Yonge Street\, T
 oronto ON M4W 2G8
LOCATION:S. Walter Stewart\, Auditorium with access to the Sensory Room
URL:https://tpl.bibliocommons.com/v2/events/69b41636b48451fc3c08a071
X-SOURCE:Toronto Public Library
END:VEVENT
