SUMMARY:After School Club
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260525T160000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260525T170000
UID:69c44d175a2d780f42c4bb02@tpl.bibliocommons.com
DESCRIPTION:Looking for something to do after school? Come out to our Afte
 r School Club and learn new things\, make stuff\, meet other kids and have
  fun!\nFor ages 6-12. DROP-IN!\nSnacks are offered during the After School
  Club for participants. Ingredient lists will be available. Snacks are gen
 erously supported\, in part\, by donors.
LOCATION:Rexdale
URL:https://tpl.bibliocommons.com/v2/events/69c44d175a2d780f42c4bb02
X-SOURCE:Toronto Public Library
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Create a DJ Set with AI Tools for Teens
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260418T140000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260418T160000
UID:69a1ff7a491b809c6f1cfc8f@tpl.bibliocommons.com
DESCRIPTION:Ever wonder how DJs create seamless mixes that keep a dance fl
 oor moving? What if you could build your own DJ set from scratch using art
 ificial intelligence?\nJoin us for a hands-on demonstration/workshop where
  you'll use AI to generate original beat-based music\, then learn how to b
 reak it down into stems\, loops\, and sections\, and then reassemble them 
 into a dynamic set you can perform live. No prior music or programming exp
 erience is required.\nRegistration is required.\nThis program is part of t
 he Innovator in Residence (AI and Music Production) program\, which is des
 igned to help beginner and intermediate learners build knowledge and creat
 ive skills and get hands-on with current AI tools in music production and 
 learn about the history\, copyright and ethics of generative music. For mo
 re information and a full list of programs\, visit tpl.ca/airesident.
LOCATION:Fairview\, Digital Innovation Hub\, 3rd Floor
URL:https://tpl.bibliocommons.com/v2/events/69a1ff7a491b809c6f1cfc8f
X-SOURCE:Toronto Public Library
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Music Copyright and Ethics in the AI Era
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260424T140000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260424T160000
UID:69a2002c491b809c6f1cfcda@tpl.bibliocommons.com
DESCRIPTION:***Please note - the time of this program has changed. We apol
 ogize for any inconvenience.***\nWhen you use AI to create music\, who act
 ually owns it? Can a melody generated by a machine infringe on someone els
 e's copyright? As AI tools become more accessible\, these questions are mo
 re relevant than ever - and the answers aren't always straightforward.\nIn
  this session\, you'll get a plain-language breakdown of how music copyrig
 ht works\, what the rules are around sampling\, and how these long-standin
 g principles apply to AI-generated music. You'll also hear about landmark 
 legal cases - both surprising victories and cautionary tales - including r
 eal-world examples from a working composer's own career.\nDrop-in\, no reg
 istration required.\n***Please note - the time of this program has changed
 . We apologize for any inconvenience.***\nThis program is part of the Inno
 vator in Residence (AI and Music Production) program\, which is designed t
 o help beginner and intermediate learners build knowledge and creative ski
 lls and get hands-on with current AI tools in music production and learn a
 bout the history\, copyright and ethics of generative music. For more info
 rmation and a full list of programs\, visit tpl.ca/airesident.
LOCATION:Fairview\, Room 201\, 2nd Floor
URL:https://tpl.bibliocommons.com/v2/events/69a2002c491b809c6f1cfcda
X-SOURCE:Toronto Public Library
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:History of Generative Music: The Early Modern Era
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260430T160000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260430T180000
UID:69a200ef1e64afd01e5e909d@tpl.bibliocommons.com
DESCRIPTION:The twentieth century brought radical new ideas about what mus
 ic could be - from compositions determined by coin tosses to pieces that r
 earranged themselves with every performance. Pioneering composers began us
 ing chance\, repetition\, and early electronics to challenge everything au
 diences thought they knew about music.\nIn this session\, you'll explore h
 ow early modern composers pushed the boundaries of generative music\, disc
 over the creative and technical mechanisms behind their experiments\, and 
 learn how their breakthroughs paved the way for the AI music tools we use 
 today.\nDrop-in\, no registration required.\nThis program is part of the I
 nnovator in Residence (AI and Music Production) program\, which is designe
 d to help beginner and intermediate learners build knowledge and creative 
 skills and get hands-on with current AI tools in music production and lear
 n about the history\, copyright and ethics of generative music. For more i
 nformation and a full list of programs\, visit\ntpl.ca/airesident\n.
LOCATION:Fairview\, Digital Innovation Hub\, 3rd Floor
URL:https://tpl.bibliocommons.com/v2/events/69a200ef1e64afd01e5e909d
X-SOURCE:Toronto Public Library
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Create Hip-Hop Music with AI Tools for Teens
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260514T160000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260514T170000
UID:69a2019f8089f23c675eb003@tpl.bibliocommons.com
DESCRIPTION:Have you ever had a melody stuck in your head and wished you c
 ould turn it into a real song? AI tools are making it easier than ever to 
 bring your musical experiences to life - but how do you make sure the musi
 c you create is truly yours?\nExplore how to use AI as a creative assistan
 t to build radio-ready hip-hop tracks based on your own original ideas. Yo
 u'll learn how to guide AI tools to serve your vision rather than replace 
 it\, and we'll cover Canadian copyright guidelines to ensure the music you
  make qualifies as your own intellectual property. No prior music or progr
 amming experience is required.\nThis program is part of the Innovator in R
 esidence (AI and Music Production) program\, which is designed to help beg
 inner and intermediate learners build knowledge and creative skills and ge
 t hands-on with current AI tools in music production and learn about the h
 istory\, copyright and ethics of generative music. For more information an
 d a full list of programs\, visit\ntpl.ca/airesident\n.
LOCATION:Fairview\, Youth Hub\, 3rd Floor
URL:https://tpl.bibliocommons.com/v2/events/69a2019f8089f23c675eb003
X-SOURCE:Toronto Public Library
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:History of Generative Music: The Last 50 Years
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260516T140000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260516T160000
UID:69a201c84dacf581ff7e6743@tpl.bibliocommons.com
DESCRIPTION:From the first computer-generated compositions to the AI music
  tools available today\, the past five decades have seen generative music 
 evolve at an extraordinary pace. What began as experiments in university l
 abs has become technology that anyone can access from a laptop or phone.\n
 In this session\, you'll trace the rapid evolution of generative music fro
 m early computer experiments through to modern AI platforms\, discover the
  key innovations that made today's tools possible\, and explore where this
  technology might be heading next.\nDrop-in. No registration required.\nTh
 is program is part of the Innovator in Residence (AI and Music Production)
  program\, which is designed to help beginner and intermediate learners bu
 ild knowledge and creative skills and get hands-on with current AI tools i
 n music production and learn about the history\, copyright and ethics of g
 enerative music. For more information and a full list of programs\, visit\
 ntpl.ca/airesident\n.
LOCATION:Fairview\, Room 201\, 2nd Floor
URL:https://tpl.bibliocommons.com/v2/events/69a201c84dacf581ff7e6743
X-SOURCE:Toronto Public Library
END:VEVENT
